<subSubSection id="C352CCA80737657680C3F9A628153879" pageId="2" pageNumber="11" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF79F230737657680C3F9A628153879" blockId="2.[151,1127,1044,1611]" pageId="2" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis id="B93C43310737657680C3F9A62B6A3819" bold="true" box="[151,280,1556,1579]" pageId="2" pageNumber="11">Etymology.</emphasis>
Derived from the combination of the Greek noun άστρο (star) and 
<collectingCountry id="F35FDFB3073765768383F9A62E523819" box="[983,1056,1556,1579]" name="Brunei" pageId="2" pageNumber="11">Brunei</collectingCountry>
which means a “star of 
<collectingCountry id="F35FDFB307376576811EF9862BE73879" box="[330,405,1588,1611]" name="Brunei" pageId="2" pageNumber="11">Brunei</collectingCountry>
” (gender neutrum).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
